scenarios.expected_interpretation:
Graves hyperthyroidism with suppressed TSH (0.01), elevated free T4 and T3; 
Positive anti-TSH receptor antibody pathognomonic for Graves; eye signs (orbitopathy) present; 
autoimmune thyroiditis

Primary hypothyroidism with elevated TSH (8.5) and low T4 (9.0); 
Positive anti-TPO antibody suggests autoimmune (Hashimoto) thyroiditis; 
requires levothyroxine replacement titrated to TSH goal

Central (secondary) hypothyroidism with low T4 (8.5) and inadequate TSH response (2.1); 
Suggests pituitary dysfunction; cortisol also low (180) with low ACTH (15) indicates 
secondary adrenal insufficiency; requires investigation of all pituitary axes

Isolated GH deficiency (IGF-1 low 35, basal GH low 0.8) with other pituitary axes intact; 
ACTH and cortisol normal, TSH normal; requires GH stimulation testing (insulin tolerance or GHRH/arginine test) 
to confirm and quantify deficiency

Acromegaly with macroadenoma (18mm), markedly elevated GH (45) and IGF-1 (850); 
Glucose fails to suppress GH on OGTT (diagnostic); glucose intolerance present (8.2 mmol/L); 
hypertension develops in 20-40%; requires surgery or medical therapy

Prolactinoma with macroadenoma (16mm); prolactin markedly elevated (2800, >>4× normal); 
Visual field loss from mass effect; amenorrhea from suppressed gonadotropins; 
First-line treatment is dopamine agonist (bromocriptine/cabergoline), not surgery

scenarios.recommended_action:
ICU admission; IV hydrocortisone 100mg STAT then 6-hourly; IV normal saline or dextrose-saline 
(rapid volume replacement); empiric antibiotics (infection likely precipitant); 
electrolyte monitoring and correction; treat underlying infection

scenarios.expected_interpretation:
Cushing syndrome with excessive cortisol (880, >2× normal) unresponsive to 1mg dexamethasone 
(no suppression indicates pathologic cortisol excess); markedly elevated 24-hr urine free cortisol (1250); 
ACTH elevated (125) suggests pituitary source (Cushing disease) rather than primary adrenal; 
Metabolic complications: hypokalemia (3.0), impaired glucose tolerance (9.5), hypertension; 
High-dose dexamethasone test would help localize (pituitary shows suppression, ectopic does not)

scenarios.recommended_action:
ICU admission; AGGRESSIVE IV hydration with normal saline (1-2 L/hr); 
diuretics (furosemide) once hydrated; bisphosphonates or denosumab; 
address underlying cause (surgery if parathyroid, treat cancer if malignancy)
